The absorption and fluorescence spectra of the BNSCDs are explored and the results are displayed in Fig. 1A. There are two absorption peaks at 281 and 351 nm (black line in Fig. 1A), which are attributed to π → π⁎ transition of the CC bond and n → π⁎ transition of the CO bond, respectively [6,20,51]. There is a broad absorption peak between 450 and 620 nm, which may be caused by functional groups on the surface of the as-prepared BNSCDs. The fluorescence excitation (red line) and emission (blue line) spectra of the BNSCDs were showed in Fig. 1A, demonstrating that the optimal excitation (λex) and emission (λem) peaks are at 571 nm and 597 nm, respectively. The BNSCDs aqueous solution could emit bright orange fluorescence under 365 nm UV light irradiation (the inset in Fig. 1A). The fluorescence behavior of the BNSCDs was further surveyed under different excitation wavelengths (λex). When the λex was changed from 370 to 580 nm, the emission wavelength (λem) was kept at ca. 597 nm, displaying the BNSCDs possess λex-independent fluorescence behavior. Furthermore, cresyl violet acetate as the reference, the quantum yield (Φ
                           s
                        ) was calculated as 11.5%, which was shown in Table S1 and Fig. S1.
